  "text": "13 It is also associated with a reduction in the potentiating effects of the stretchshortening cycle. Consequently, the metabolic energy spent to achieve the same velocity is higher in the uphill than in the horizontal plane. Reduced yield observed during uphill running can be explained in part by mechanical and kinematic alterations, [CITATION_1] which are revealed as changes of the physiological profile. In fact, the are many determinants of aerobic performance, and perhaps the neuromuscular contribution is of greater importance when running up a slope than other factors. However, this still needs to be properly investigated. [CITATION_2] Swanson and Caldwell [CITATION_3] have suggested an important role of running economy reflecting negatively on the uphill running performance. It seems that changes above or below the optimum kinematic pattern exerts deleterious influences, increasing metabolic cost and perceived exertion in uphill running. [CITATION_4] Snyder and Farley 29 reported a U-shaped",
